Alright, I'm getting a bunch of DMs about how it's done, so instead of waiting, I'll just post it here.
It's pretty straightforward.

powv wants to check a specific layer.

input_sum + output_sum % num_param_groups = layer_index

I don't have control over input_sum, but I do control output_sum (and the mechanism doesn't check output tokens - very silly), and I've got 100k tokens available in llama3 and only 195 num_param_groups (y'all are using a small model).

This means I can pick one of my 100k tokens so that the simple math lands on a layer_index of my choice.
I think I picked 4, since it's a small 4k vector.

This means you can run powv on a CPU machine with just the 4k vector loaded.

To pass, just take the input prompt, calculate its sum, then pick an output token ID that makes the math land on layer index 4.

The rest of the mechanism is kind of a joke, it's just simple arithmetic with some mods using values within that layer.

Just to elaborate on this a bit more.  The new mechanism has two additional functions:
- fast pass to compare every single token's logprob
- slow pass to spot check first, random, and last logprob

Logprobs are heavily, heavily affected by sampling params and quantization, which makes them a much more reliable (yet finnicky) validation mechanism.

In the fast pass, the entire prompt + output text from miner is concatenated into a single prompt, then a single additional throwaway token is generated with `prompt_logprobs=True` which forces logprob calculating for every input token (which by this point also includes the output tokens from the miner).  Input processing is quite fast in comparison to generating outputs, so this check is fairly quick, and therefore can potentially be gamed by injecting proper logprobs after the fact.

The slower pass is to catch if miners try to be sneaky and calculate logprobs for quantized output after the fact, in which it generates a single token at random offsets.

To be very clear, this is *HEAVILY* influenced by @namoray 's validation mechanism on sn19.  The loop is quite different in the fact that it uses prompt_logprobs vs only generating random tokens, but the concept (comparing logprobs of miner output to validator logprobs) remains.

# @targon・4 Announcing Targon v4 (and Happy birthday to us!)
This is a massive, breaking change for validators. Miners will also need to upgrade their infrastructure, however the miner code will remain the same.
## Whats new?
- Validators can choose which models they want to query, on demand.
Miners are now scored not only on speed, but how many models they can run at a time. Early next week we will have a dashboard on stats showing what model each validator could possibly send as a challenge. 

- Safer validator subtensor code
Validators now use a separate thread to handle block updates. This means things like setting weights, updating the metagraph, etc, are much more stable and overall easier to work with.

- New verifier docker image
Validators now require docker installed on the machine they are running targon on. Targon manages the lifetimes of verifier docker images in order to verify the outputs of each model run on the subnet. 

- Multiple model choice methods
Validators can choose to either mimic the most popular models, their own list in a text document, or the old nouse model (as a default)

- Lots of refactoring
A lot, im serious.
## When?
We will release v4 on Monday, October 7th at 1PM CST.
## How can I try it out?
v4 is live on testnet uid 40. Checkout the v4 branch at https://github.com/manifold-inc/targon/tree/feat/v4

The readme is mostly up to date, but there is still a bit missing regarding model endpoints and such. We should have those in and ready by mondays release. Cheers!
